fields.title: Top Gun: Maverick
fields.review: Top Gun: Maverick pulls off a feat even trickier than a 4G inverted dive, delivering a long-belated sequel that surpasses its predecessor in wildly entertaining style.

fields.title: Nope
fields.review: Admirable for its originality and ambition even when its reach exceeds its grasp, Nope adds Spielbergian spectacle to Jordan Peele's growing arsenal.

fields.title: Dragon Ball Super: Super Hero
fields.review: Blending beautifully animated action with fresh character development, Dragon Ball Super: Super Hero is everything fans of the franchise will be looking for.

fields.title: Knives Out
fields.review: Knives Out sharpens old murder-mystery tropes with a keenly assembled suspense outing that makes brilliant use of writer-director Rian Johnson's stellar ensemble.

fields.title: Bullet Train
fields.review: Bullet Train's colorful cast and high-speed action are almost enough to keep things going after the story runs out of track.

fields.title: Everything Everywhere All at Once
fields.review: Led by an outstanding Michelle Yeoh, Everything Everywhere All at Once lives up to its title with an expertly calibrated assault on the senses.

fields.title: The Batman
fields.review: A grim, gritty, and gripping super-noir, The Batman ranks among the Dark Knight's bleakest -- and most thrillingly ambitious -- live-action outings.

fields.title: Baby Driver
fields.review: Stylish, exciting, and fueled by a killer soundtrack, Baby Driver hits the road and it's gone -- proving fast-paced action movies can be smartly written without sacrificing thrills.

fields.title: Jojo Rabbit
fields.review: Jojo Rabbit's blend of irreverent humor and serious ideas definitely won't be to everyone's taste -- but either way, this anti-hate satire is audacious to a fault.

fields.title: Pinocchio (2022)
fields.review: Visually dazzling but soulless, the largely inert Pinocchio reaffirms that you should always let your conscience be your guideâ€¦ away from unnecessary remakes.

fields.title: Last Night in Soho
fields.review: Although it struggles to maintain its thrilling early momentum, Last Night in Soho shows flashes of Edgar Wright at his most stylish and ambitious.

fields.title: The Lighthouse
fields.review: A gripping story brilliantly filmed and led by a pair of powerhouse performances, The Lighthouse further establishes Robert Eggers as a filmmaker of exceptional talent.

fields.title: Parasite
fields.review: An urgent, brilliantly layered look at timely social themes, Parasite finds writer-director Bong Joon Ho in near-total command of his craft.

fields.title: Evangelion: 3.0+1.0 Thrice Upon a Time
fields.review: Thrice Upon a Time is as imperfect as anything in the Evangelion franchise, but as Anno's last word on the franchise, it might just be a perfect ending.

fields.title: Sonic The Hedgehog 2
fields.review: A fun, fast-paced improvement on the original, Sonic the Hedgehog 2 is like a video game come to life -- and for once where a movie's concerned, that's actually a compliment.
